"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The np.sinc function in numpy returns the sinc function, which is defined as sinc(x) = sin(pi*x)/(pi*x). When x is zero, sinc(x) is defined to be 1. However, due to floating point precision issues, the result of sinc(0) might not be exactly 1 when computed using np.sinc. Therefore, comparing sinc_result[0] to 1 using the '==' operator might fail. A similar issue might occur when comparing sinc_result[1] to 0.\",\n  \"patch\": \"7c7\\n<assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n---\\n>assert np.isclose(sinc_result[0], 1), \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n8c8\\n<assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n>assert np.isclose(sinc_result[1], 0), \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\"\n}"